# Due to the sheer number of commits from Raspberry Pi (raspberrypi/linux), it
# is no longer possible to maintain a patch set in autobuild/patches.
# Maintainers should use the following procedure to bump version:
#
# - In AOSC-Tracking/linux, branch off `aosc/vx.y.z' into `aosc/vx.y.z-rpi',
#   in accordance with the Raspberry Pi versioning.
#   Note that the branching-off point might need to be earlier than branch tip
#   to exclude some loongarch64 specific patches. These patches (currently)
#   might not build correctly on other architectures.
# - Merge latest `rpi-x.y.y' from raspberrypi/linux into `aosc/vx.y.z-rpi',
#   based on the closest stable tag from `rpi-x.y.y'.
#   - In case `rpi-x.y.y` has a newer stable tag than that of `aosc/vx.y.z`,
#     find and pick the tip of rpi-specific changes using git log --graph.
# - Cherry-pick commits that come after the merge in other `vx.y.z-rpi*' tags,
#   such as 8d8518b0d3d180d00db557478d79a059e969d042.
# - Push your changes to AOSC-Tracking/linux, tagging the latest patchset as
#   `vx.y.z-rpi${date}`, with date corresponding to the CommitDate of the rpi
#   branch.

# Downstream kernels often rebase upon upstream releases.
# For use inside autobuild/
__VER=6.18.25
# Use this for stable releases.
PATCH_DATE=20260429
VER="${__VER}+rpi${PATCH_DATE}"

SRCS="git::commit=tags/v${__VER}-rpi${PATCH_DATE}::https://github.com/AOSC-Tracking/linux.git"
CHKSUMS="SKIP"
